INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','article',0,28,28,'und',0,'<p>Cassandra Lewis builds up a preacher’s steam as she stands in her living room, talking about her faith and her fight against banks.</p><p>The big banks have taken Lewis’ mother’s home. Her friends’ homes. Now the banks are trying to take her home.</p><p>But they cannot bully a 58-year-old black woman who grew up in Birmingham, Alabama during the Civil Rights Movement</p><p>“If I give up, that means I gave up on God,” Lewis says. “Like he had a ram in the bush for Abraham, he has this ram for me.”</p><p>If there’s a typical route to home foreclosure, it is not Lewis’ story.</p><p>“This is a very complicated case, this house is,” Lewis says, laughing. Even when she talks about the possibility of losing her home, Lewis laughs and smiles a lot. But don’t mistake that gaiety for a lack of determination; she has fought for years, chronicling every step she’s taken.</p><p>Stories of home foreclosures often can be told in giant stacks of paperwork. Lewis carried the letters, contracts and court documents in a blue shopping bag for months She took them to work. She took them to the store. She even brought them to church, because she couldn’t bear to think that if her car was stolen, her paperwork would be lost.</p><p>She didn’t let the bag out of her site until she delivered it to a lawyer, who’s taken her case pro bono.</p><p>Lewis’ daughter bought the house 18 years ago. In 1999, the daughter moved to Las Vegas, and since then, Lewis and various other family members have lived in the house. The trouble started in 2006, when a cousin lived there, and got behind in payments by a couple of months. Lewis’ daughter got several letters from a company with a seemingly self-explanatory name: Keep Your Home Solutions.</p><p>Her daughter drew up a contract with the company: If the family kept up mortgage payments for two years, the home would revert fully to their ownership. No worries.</p><p>But there was a catch: While Lewis and her family were faithfully making payments to Keep Your Home Solutions, the company sold the house to Brian D. John.</p><p>John used equity in the house to take out a loan. His failure to keep up those payments has led to pain and harassment for Lewis.</p><p>The documentation Lewis didn’t give to lawyers remains in her home. She keeps recordings of daily phone calls from an employee of a real estate agency, offering her cash for keys to her house. Lewis has two years’ worth of date books in which she’s noted every time the same real estate agent came to her home The visits became so frequent she began sleeping on her couch near the front door, fully clothed, dreading the day deputies would drag her from her home.</p><p>This type of stress is typical for people facing imminent foreclosure, says Ben Hanna, organizing director at the Colorado Progressive Coalition. The coalition has been working with homeowners to stop foreclosure for about a year, and in October organized a week of actions against big banks’ lending practices.</p><p>“Can you imagine living month to month with a foreclosure sales date?” Hanna says. “And then a month out, it changes?”</p><p>Lewis says the feeling is like something out of a horror movie.</p><p>“I can’t even describe it,” she says. “Although these are just material things, you believe in God, but it makes you feel like you want to kill yourself. I see this and it’s like they’re trying to take a person’s heart out.”</p><p>The closest Lewis has come to eviction was last year, when her house was up for auction at the courthouse.&nbsp; By chance, nobody bid. A judge has since ruled the home cannot be sold until issues surrounding the ownership are cleared up.</p><p>Lewis sleeps a little easier, in her bedroom. But she still checks her front door every day to see if any court papers have been served.</p><p>While fighting for her own home, Lewis has been encouraged to help others keep their houses. She volunteers at CPC’s actions against banks, and at protests cheers louder than most others in the crowd.</p><p>“I won’t give up,” Lewis says. “We have got to get the word out.”</p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','article',0,29,29,'und',0,'<blockquote><p>Dear Queer Radical,</p><div style=\"background-color: transparent; \"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; \">My friend and collaborator is a 33-year-old mother of five and in an open relationship with her husband. We were at a social movement conference and Mommy wound up sleeping with a younger guy, probably nineteen or twenty. As a fellow mother (though monogamous), I called her out. If she were a guy hitting on a younger woman, nobody would put up with that shit. Now she’s pissed at me. Did I do the right thing? </span><br><br><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; \">Monogomous Mary</span><br><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; \">Austin, TX</span><br><br>&nbsp;</div></blockquote><div style=\"background-color: transparent; \"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; \">Dear Monogamous Mary,</span><br><br><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; \">Seriously, you’re asking Queer Radical if you did the right thing? When I was 20 I was running around bathhouses sucking 60-year-old cocks and loving every inch of them. I adored those guys and am grateful to this day for all I learned. If someone had called them out for being “fucked up,” it would have stripped me of my hard-won autonomy and pleasure. I did what I wanted, with whom I wanted, assuming they wanted it too. </span><br><br><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; \">My guess is that your 19-year-old boy was thrilled to be sleeping with your mommy friend. You don’t indicate he was uncomfortable with it. You don’t indicate he didn’t like it. You don’t indicate he didn’t initiate it.</span><br><br><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; \">If he wants Mommy and Mommy wants him, there is no problem. It’s consensual sex, plain and simple.</span><br><br><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; \">Be real. You’re not only fronting sex-negativity; you’re also acting Mom-negative. If you want to support parents in social movements, allow them room to embrace the fullness of their beings. It’s the least you can do to support their role in our collective liberation.</span><br><br><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; \">You’re pissy because your friend’s getting laid and you’re so full of resentment, you can’t enjoy your own sexuality. Jerk off. Go fuck. Open up your relationship. Do whatever it takes to satisfy yourself so that you behave kindly to your friend. Bonds between mothers and collaborators matter.</span><br><br><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; \">Don’t give me some half-baked argument about age and consent that strips away a younger person’s agency. And certainly don’t act like everybody would be pissed off if a younger woman and an older man were sleeping together. I support consenting adults fucking. So do a lot of people who don’t hate sexuality.</span><br><br><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; \">We all have a right to decide what we want to do with our own and other consenting adults’ bodies. It’s a basic feminist principle.</span><br><br><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; \">Newsflash: Young people have brains and use them.</span><br><br><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; \">Mutual aid, mutual pleasure, and mutual masturbation: these are social movements in action. Consensus reached?</span><br><br><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; \">Go apologize now. </span><br><br><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; \">Sans Solidarity,</span><br><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; \">Queer Radical</span></div>','Dear Queer Radical:   My friend and collaborator is a 33-year-old mother of five and in an open relationship with her husband. We were at a social movement conference and Mommy wound up sleeping with a younger guy','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','article',0,30,30,'und',0,'<p>There are phone book worth of reasons the Mississippi personhood ballot measure lacks merit. The initiative – which voters will consider today – defines personhood as beginning at conception.</p><p>Sperm, meet Egg. Congratulations! You’re a person now.</p><p>Pro-choice and women’s health advocates have rallied against the Personhood Amendment, and rightfully so. As written, it seems designed to limit access to some birth control, stem-cell research and its obvious target, abortion.</p><p>Ah, abortion. That’s where debate always gets sticky.</p><p>Most critiques of Amendment 26 include a phrase that goes like this: the Personhood Amendment bans abortion, even in cases of rape or incest. Some, generously, will add the concern of risk to a potential mother’s life. This problematic language gets thrown into the abortion debate a lot in order to convince – wait, who?</p><p>For those who think life begins at conception, the embryo is a life, no matter how it’s begotten. In fact, PersonhoodMississippi.com answers the “what about abortion?” question by linking to<a href=\"http://www.rebeccakiessling.com/\"> Rebecca Kiessling’s website</a>.&nbsp;Kiessling is a radically pro-life speaker whose primary mission seems to be encouraging rape victims not to abort – after all, her own life is a result of rape.&nbsp; So that camp might feel sympathy for a pregnant rape victim, but by their logic, she is still a murderer if she refuses to incubate that cellular clump of person.</p><p>An important component of pro-choice arguments is that people can make reasonable decisions about their health, their bodies and their lives. So pregnant women can decide to abort whether their birth control failed, they were raped, they lost their jobs, they were victims of incest, their partner is no longer supportive and they don’t wish to parent alone – or even if they just don’t want to buy maternity jeans with the stretchy front panel. The circumstances shouldn’t make a difference.</p><p>But surely, there are people on the fence. People who think abortion might be OK if - if what? If the potential mother has suffered something horrible? If she has no other choice but to die?</p><p>Let’s stipulate that when you add rape, incest or life-or-death medical decisions to any circumstance, you make it worse: child abuse, a burglary, work, pregnancy, dating. Naturally, these factors are a layer of trauma atop the decision to abort or not. People dealing with these issues should have every tool available for dealing with pregnancy. &nbsp;As should everyone else facing an unwanted pregnancy.</p><p>Arguments that we must specially allow for abortion in cases of rape, incest or if a pregnancy is life-threatening weaken the pro-choice viewpoint. They grind away at the legitimate claim that people should be able to end pregnancies for any reason.</p><p>Too often in discussions of debates framed as women’s issues, deference is given to those who can easily be painted as innocent victims. There is support for a woman, so long as that support comes in the form of protective aid. That notion alone insults women trying to make the best choices for themselves and their families.</p><p>But it also implies there is something shameful, something less valid about abortions that aren’t the result of violence or life-threatening ailments.&nbsp; Dragging out the “even in cases of rape or incest” language, creates a hierarchy of good abortions (Under duress! Unforeseeable conditions!) vs. bad abortions (Slutty sex! Poor people making bad choices!)</p><p>This line of rhetoric does nothing to improve abortion’s image as the reasonable and personal medical decision that it is.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>-- <em>Leslie Wilber is a journalist who has covered legal issues, police misconduct, high school sports and various other disastrous things. She\'s currently an editor at The Precarious.</em></p><p>&nbsp;</p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','article',0,31,32,'und',0,'<p>Notorious Bavarian filmmaker, <a href=\"http://www.wernerherzog.com/\">Werner Herzog</a> returns to the screen this winter with <a href=\"http://www.wernerherzog.com/114.html\"><em>Into the Abyss - A Tale of Death, A Tale of Life</em></a>, a meditation on capital punishment in the United States.&nbsp; Herzog offers an expertly crafted, startlingly intimate portrait of two young men: one serving out a life sentence, the other a death row inmate.&nbsp;</p><p>Once friends, the two men were convicted separately for their involvement in the same triple homicide. Ten years later, Michael Perry sits on death row, 8 days away from his scheduled execution. His former friend, Jason Burkett has served 10 years of a life sentence. He awaits 40 years before his first chance for parole.</p><p>Herzog exploits his knack for capturing human moments and helps his audience identify with even the most disturbing or enigmatic of subjects.&nbsp; Through thoughtful, prodding and often staged interviews, Herzog paints a complex picture of the murders, the grief of the victim’s families, and of the lives of Burkett and Perry since their convictions.&nbsp;</p><p>Famous for over-the-top editorializing, Herzog’s <i>Into the Abyss</i>&nbsp;omits his traditional voice-over narration. He opts instead to use his own off-camera comments during one of his interviews with Perry to make his position on capital punishment clear.&nbsp; “I do not have to like you,” says Herzog to a smiling Perry, “but I respect you and you are a human being, and I do not believe that human beings should be executed.”&nbsp;</p><p>While Herzog does state his personal feelings on capital punishment, the film avoids directly calling out the brutality and injustice of the U.S. criminal justice system.&nbsp; Rather, Herzog remains emotionally tied to the stories of the two young men.&nbsp; The effect is haunting, if not rallying.&nbsp;</p><p>Fresh off the success of last year’s <a href=\"http://www.wernerherzog.com/114.html\"><em>Cave of Forgotten Dreams</em></a>, Herzog makes a return to his best known and often most entertaining territory with <em>Abyss</em>: moody, character driven documentaries that ask probing, deep questions about the human experience.</p><p>Herzog has a gift for telling deeply personal human stories, and for fans of his work, <em>Into the Abyss</em> will be no disappointment.&nbsp; Newcomers on the other hand, might find his somber tone and unusual style hard to digest.&nbsp;</p><p>For those interested in a more pointed send up of the US criminal justice system, the French documentary <em>Murder on a Sunday Morning</em> (Lestrade, 2001), also a case study involving an U.S. teenage murder convict, offers a more cohesive storyline and more traditional documentary structure.&nbsp; <em>Into the Abyss</em> opens Nov. 11. &nbsp;</p><p><strong>--Erica Gleichman</strong></p><p><i>Erica Gleichman writes movie reviews for The Precarious</i><strong><em>, </em></strong><em>studied Film Studies at The University of Colorado - Denver and currently lives in San Diego, California.</em></p>','Notorious Bavarian filmmaker, Werner Herzog returns to the screen this winter with Into the Abyss - A Tale of Death, A Tale of Life, a meditation on capital punishment in the United States.  Herzog offers an expertly crafted, startlingly intimate portrait of two young men: one serving out a life sentence, the other a death row inmate. ','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','article',0,32,33,'und',0,'<p>When it comes to debates about privacy, the notion that it’s a shield for something sinister often arises.</p><p>To assuage the worries of folks who hold this point of view I will start by saying this: I have nothing to hide. I freely admit I was sitting in my living room, eating hummus with a spoon and listening to <a href=\"http://www.npr.org/programs/talk-of-the-nation/\">Talk of the Nation</a> when I started thinking about privacy this week. On the radio, they were talking about a case &nbsp;before the Supreme Court, in which the justices will decide if it was OK for police to attach a GPS device to Antoine Jones’ Jeep and track it 24/7 for nearly a month. For all but 10 days police had no warrant to use the GPS device. &nbsp;</p><p>It’s a pretty obvious – and easy – analysis to say giving police greater ability to track people is a quick route to eroding what little protection we have against the authorities. That justices more than once<a href=\"http://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/supreme-court-worries-that-new-technology-creates-1984-scenarios/2011/11/08/gIQAbHdw2M_story.html\"> drew parallels</a> between this case and the novel “1984” speaks to the level of intrusion this represents.</p><p>As I listened to the radio, a caller told the host people with nothing to hide wouldn’t worry about this type of surveillance. &nbsp;Since then, I couldn’t help but read comments about this case that echo this sentiment. While I maintain I have nothing to hide, I worry that this is alarmingly wishful thinking.</p><p>The police perception of who is suspicious and who is not can vary widely for many reasons, most notably perhaps, race and perceived economic status.</p><p>In this case, tracking Jones’ car led police to a stash of drugs and a stack of cash.</p><p>If he didn’t have all that coke, he wouldn’t be in trouble, some argue. And to some extent, that’s true: an absence of powder-filled baggies can certainly help a person beat drug charges.</p><p>But with each examination of Fourth Amendment rights, examples of innocent people who have been bothered by police, imprisoned or fined are bound to turn up. The police don’t just investigate the guilty.</p><p>The Jones case reminds me of fallout from Arizona vs. Gant, a case heard by the Supreme Court in 2009, while I was reporting on courts in South Texas. Like Jones, Gant dealt with just how much police can snoop into our cars; the justices decided that searching a car after arrest without a warrant is not legal.</p><p>In the local court system I covered, the first case to be reconsidered because of this ruling was that of a 31-year-old man, stopped about a block from his home. &nbsp;Although he didn’t have his driver’s license on him, his girlfriend was able to bring it to the scene within moments.</p><p>Still, he was arrested and his car was searched without a warrant. In the glove compartment, there was a plastic baggie with a film of cocaine residue. He was charged with possession and put through a lot of hassle.</p><p>“Good!” said some online commenters. “Let’s not protect the guilty!”</p><p>The problem is, this man was not found guilty of any crimes. There was nothing in the car that could actually get a person high – just an empty plastic bag. Since his license was produced on the scene, he couldn’t be fined for driving without one.</p><p>In the end police could offer evidence of only one misdemeanor, the very thing he was first pulled over for: playing his radio too loud.</p><p>Essentially, he spent nine months entangled in the legal system although he had nothing to hide, except, perhaps, his taste in music.&nbsp;</p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','article',0,33,35,'und',0,'<p>Look at the image of the media truck toppled on its side by rioters. One might jump to the conclusion that the Occupy Movement got bold, that class war finally meant something and that people were outraged by the failure of corporate media.</p><p>Yeah right. This is the United States. That act of property destruction couldn’t be the product of a political riot. Activists don’t get that angry. Only one thing could cause that—sports.</p><p>Penn State fires the coach. Students riot. Schools raise tuition, states cut school budgets, the military’s poverty draft compels more youth to die overseas, corporations continue to pillage the earth, and hundreds of thousands of people lose their homes to banks. The public remains largely calm.</p><p>Why do people in the United States appear to care more about their football team than the political moment we live in?</p><p>It is easy to come to the quick assumption that people in the U.S. are stupid, lazy, disconnected and largely apathetic; however, a riot, even a sports riot, suggests something quite different. Americans feel more powerful at a sports game than at the ballot, more inspired by athletes than by politicians and activists and more loyal to coaches than to social movement elders.</p><p>Why does the appeal of sports figures trump that of U.S. politicians? Quite simply, the athletes are more inspiring. A good coach rallies team morale, pleases its fans by taking risks, coordinates bold maneuvers and never shies away from a good fight. Players serve fans by sticking to their guns and winning games.</p><p>In contrast, the political establishment thrives on betraying its fans, the voters who believed, the people allegedly represented. The representatives’ loyalty is to the wealthy and to the middle road between the richest of the rich and the richest of the middle class.</p><p>Political compromise sells out the vast majority of us, whom nobody in Washington or the boardrooms of corporations represents.</p><p>It’s not as though the joy of sports remains untouched by the malevolence of corporate interest. Corporations have found ways of compromising athletics with advertising. More horrifically, they have bought off the basic democratic concept of rule by the people.</p><p>Consider Halliburton. They will never determine who wins a ballgame. They will influence who gets elected and what policies are passed.</p><p>People rightly think they have more power eating a hotdog and doing the wave than voting, meeting with politicians and struggling for reform. Political reform is a dead end road for those aiming for social change.</p><p>What the public has forgotten, in its political disenchantment, is the power of the riot—something the politically engaged could relearn from sports fans. Perhaps one day, home foreclosures, tuition increases, and police brutality will spark riots as readily as football coach firings.</p><p><strong>--Kyle Harris</strong></p><p>Kyle Harris is an editor at <a href=\"http://theprecarious.com\">The Precarious</a>, Co-Producer at <a href=\"http://improbablepictures.com\">Improbable Pictures</a>, and author of the blog <a href=\"http://queerradical.com\">Queer Radical</a>.&nbsp;</p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','article',0,34,37,'und',0,'<p>Across the world, the Occupy uprising continues, students revolt against tuition hikes and social movements are graced with a small victory and impacted by significant loss.</p><p>Last Sunday thousands gathered around the White House protesting the <a href=\"http://green.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/11/10/keystone-pipeline-decision-could-be-delayed/?scp=3&amp;sq=keystone%20delay&amp;st=cse\">Keystone XL Pipeline</a>. Days later, Obama postponed the project until after the 2012 election.</p><p>In <a href=\"http://live.montrealgazette.com/Event/Montreal_students_protest_rising_tuition_fees\">Montreal</a> riot police confronted thousands of students, the teachers association and unions at McGill University for rising up in a General Strike against tuition increases.&nbsp; In total, approximately <a href=\"http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/up-to-200000-quebec-students-stage-massive-protest-over-tuition-hikes/article2232146/\">200,000 marched</a> in Quebec to protest tuition hikes in the province.&nbsp;</p><p>In London police feared nearly <a href=\"http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/law-and-order/8877436/Huge-police-presence-ahead-of-student-demonstration.html\">10,000 students</a> will be rioting in the streets today after tuition hikes were announced. Police responded in numbers not seen since this summer’s riots and last year’s student attacks on the Conservative Party headquarters.</p><p>In the United States, students with other priorities rioted for a different reason. Burning with rage after Penn State fired coach Joe Paterno, football fanatics fought the police, tore down traffic lights and toppled a corporate media van.</p><p>This week, the <a href=\"http://occupytogether.org\">Occupy Movement</a> incurred several losses.</p><p>Yesterday, one day after <a href=\"http://www.gogolbordello.com/\">Gogol Bordello</a> played a show for <a href=\"http://www.burlingtonfreepress.com/article/20111110/NEWS02/111110019/Breaking-Police-respond-apparent-shooting-City-Hall-Park-scene-Occupy-Burlington?odyssey=mod|breaking|text|FRONTPAGE\">Occupy Burlington</a>, a 35 year-old veteran died from a self-inflicted gunshot wound.&nbsp;</p><p>Shortly after, in <a href=\"http://gawker.com/5858608/second-fatal-shooting-near-an-occupy-protest-wont-be-good-for-pr\">Oakland</a>, another man was shot 30 feet from the Occupy Oakland encampment. The ever-shifty Mayor Jean Quan is demanding once again that protestors shut down their camp.</p><p>In <a href=\"http://www.sltrib.com/sltrib/news/52896438-78/occupy-park-protesters-pioneer.html.csp\">Salt Lake City</a>, a man died at an Occupy protest from carbon monoxide poison due to a space heater and a possible drug overdose. As winter creeps into colder states, city and state officials are confronted with the decision to eject protestors from parks, incur further deaths or allow protestors to build reasonable shelters to protect themselves from the elements.</p><p>Berkeley police beat students who were sitting on the ground, arms linked, nonviolently defending their encampment. Twenty-two students, 1 professor and 16 others were arrested at the demonstration. <a href=\"http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=%2Fc%2Fa%2F2011%2F11%2F11%2FMNH21LTC4D.DTL\">The San Francisco Chronicle</a>&nbsp;quoted Berkeley University of California Police Captain Margo Bennett, who has drawn significant criticism for stating, “The individuals who linked arms and actively resisted, that in and of itself was violent.”</p><p>In happier Occupy news, a group calling itself <a href=\"http://occupywallst.org/article/occupy-highway-99-march-washington/\">Occupy the Highway</a>, has begun a journey from Wall Street to Washington D.C. taking the message of Occupy Wall Street on the road.</p><p>Finally, the Ukrainian feminist group <a href=\"http://www.businessinsider.com/watch-topless-protest-at-the-vatican-2011-11\">Femen</a> staged a topless demonstration at the Vatican, declaring their rejection of&nbsp; \"Papal patriarchal propaganda manipulated by the medieval idea of a woman\'s social and cultural mission.\"</p><p>From Vermont to the Vatican, that is this week’s Fragments From the Streets. If you have actions you would like us to report, please get in touch with us <a href=\"mailto:kyle@theprecarious.com?subject=Fragments%20From%20the%20Streets\">here</a>. Until then, Happy liberation!</p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','article',0,35,38,'und',0,'<p>Roughly 7.9 million homes are in foreclosure across the United States. Though it’s a grim statistic, organizers are using those numbers to their advantage, by recruiting those who have been affected by foreclosure to fight against big banks.</p><p>Recently, The Precarious profiled people who became activists after facing the possibility of losing their homes. &nbsp;</p><p>“You have to get other people involved,” said homeowner Leonard McWilliams. In 2009, protesters helped McWilliams delay foreclosure by making a human chain around his house. In turn, he and his two teenage sons have participated in several actions against banks, including the Mile-High Showdown in Denver last month.</p><p>During the Showdown, members of the<a href=\"http://progressivecoalition.org/\"> Colorado Progressive Coalition</a>&nbsp;protested Wells Fargo’s business practices. Dozens of activists closed a large downtown branch of the bank for part of the afternoon. Cristie Drumm , vice president of communications for Wells Fargo in Colorado, said the bank closed because of safety concerns.</p><p>Massachusetts protesters with<a href=\"http://clvu.org/\"> City Life/Vida Urbana</a>&nbsp;similarly occupied a Wells Fargo in Revere, Mass. on Oct. 28. Some members of that group had been arrested while linking arms outside the headquarters of Bank of America in September.</p><p>Drumm said Wells Fargo understands that many people are frustrated with the weak economy and high foreclosure rates.</p><p>“We’re helping struggling homeowners stay in their homes,” Drumm said. “We’re working hard and we’re committed to doing more.”</p><p>Nationally, The New Bottom Line launched its widely publicized “Move our Money “campaign last week. The goal is to move $1 billion from big banks to credit unions and smaller financial institutions. According to the group, customers have so far moved $50 million from national banks.</p><p>These actions are effective because they grab the attention of mainstream media, said Ben Hanna, organizing director with CPC. Local television, radio and <a href=\"http://www.denverpost.com/breakingnews/ci_19216797\">The Denver Post</a>&nbsp;covered CPC’s week of actions.</p><p>“This is all about visibility,” he said. “We were successful because we were able to communicate to a larger audience.”</p><p>Though some high-profile events have passed, there are ongoing group efforts to stop home foreclosure.</p><p>Sharon McKee credits CPC with helping her save the northeast Denver home she’s lived in for 16 years. She felt like dealing with banks had become a full-time, fruitless job.</p><p>“It becomes your life,” McKee said. Members of the CPC wrote letters to McKee’s bank, demanding a loan modification, which was recently granted. The coalition continues to work on similar efforts with homeowners.</p><p>“Our work hasn’t ended,” Hanna said.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.newbottomline.com/\">The New Bottom Line</a>&nbsp;offers information on getting involved with the fight against home foreclosure nationally.</p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','article',0,39,46,'und',0,'<p>test</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><img alt=\"\" class=\"image-left\" src=\"http://theprecarious.com/sites/default/files/field/image/mittromney.jpg\" style=\"padding: 5px; margin-right: 5px; border-width: 2px; border-style: solid; width: 312px; height: 208px; float: left;\" title=\"hoping for a &lt;em&gt;caption&lt;/em&gt;.\">Over the last 200 years, almost entirely as a result of the U. S. union movement, workers have achieved an impressive array of protections and rights.&nbsp; Included in these are some basic rights to organize and to receive overtime pay.&nbsp; An employer cannot cheat workers out of wages, beat them, expose them to extremely dangerous or toxic environments without protection, sexually harass them, and in many cases, cannot discriminate against them.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><img alt=\"\" class=\"image-right\" src=\"http://theprecarious.com/sites/default/files/field/image/mittromney.jpg\" style=\"padding: 5px; margin-left: 5px; border-width: 2px; border-style: solid; float: right; height: 167px; width: 250px;\" title=\"and also a second caption\">It should also be noted that many laws and regulations do not apply to the agricultural industry. Not that the laws are effective, as instances of <a href=\"http://www.globalresearch.ca/index.php?context=va&amp;aid=12576\">modern day slavery</a> are found from California to Florida.&nbsp; Additionally, many U.S. territories, such as the Marianas Islands, are essentially export processing zones, where almost all worker protections found in the states are absent.&nbsp; Here workers labor under sweatshop conditions, competitively exporting goods that have a “Made in the U.S.A.” label.&nbsp; Of course, these conditions can also be found in LA, New York, and Chicago.&nbsp; The U.S. Labor Department estimates that 50% of all sewing shops in the United States are <a href=\"http://www.mtholyoke.edu/%7Enshah/fashioncrimes/Sweatshops.html\">illegal sweatshops</a>.</p>','','full_html');
