INSERT INTO `field_revision_body` VALUES ('node','page',0,8,8,'und',0,'<p>The Precarious is a media project with a mission to use in-depth journalism, storytelling and cultural analysis to re-frame the revolutionary as regular. We will investigate oppression and celebrate liberation with relentless curiosity, critical minds, style and humor. We\'re not here to merely convey information, and we hope our readers aren\'t content to idly consume media.</p><p>To meet these goals we must:</p><ol><li>Inform and surprise</li><li>Inspire action</li><li>Generate thought, debate and feeling</li><li>Destroy and create</li><li>Build solidarity</li><li>Unearth joy and horror&nbsp;</li></ol><p>&nbsp;</p><p>At The Precarious, we believe media can aid communities building a world where people determine the quality of their own lives, control the means of production, freely associate, combat all oppressions, celebrate community and individuality, build autonomy and cultural and ecological resilience, and share the fruits of labor based in need. We tell dramatic stories of communities confronting oppression. <a href=\"mailto:info@theprecarious.com\">Contact us</a> for mor information. For website related questions contact our web collective at admin@theprecarious.com.</p><p>The Precarious is a project of <a href=\"http://www.cndc.org/\">The Colorado Nonprofit Development Center</a>.</p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_revision_body` VALUES ('node','article',0,12,12,'und',0,'<p>Sometimes an enemy stumbles into the role of an ally. Consider the case of Theophilus Eugene “Bull” Connor,” Birmingham, Alabama’s Commissioner of Public Safety during the Civil Rights Movement. Connor’s claim to fame was leading law enforcement to use fire hoses and vicious dogs to attack black people demanding equal rights.</p><p>The unforgettable images of Connor’s thugs attacking demonstrators swayed a generation to fight for the civil rights of black people in the U.S. South. In an attempt to extinguish dissent, his brand of overt state violence fanned the flames of rebellion throughout the country.</p><p>Consider the phrase, “If it bleeds, it leads.” Violent repression of dissent tends to bring media attention to people under attack. Successful social movements rely on conflict with the police to make headlines and build sympathy with the public at large.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.google.com/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=5&amp;sqi=2&amp;ved=0CE4QFjAE&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.actuporalhistory.org%2F&amp;ei=1L2xTsuFB-SKiAKusIEV&amp;usg=AFQjCNHWlH1nSBrYgoabVg1VbD6iy8mLAg&amp;sig2=hHjjko9I9kX03-03_uqHdg\">ACT-UP</a>, the movement against the Vietnam War and the protests against the World Trade Organization in Seattle owed their public prominence to a blood-thirsty media intrigued by police repression. Fascinated by gore, the media brought these otherwise invisible struggles into the public imagination.</p><p>In the past weeks police have waged attacks on people camping out in parks and participating in the <a href=\"http://occupywallst.org/\">Occupy Wall Street Movement</a>. In search for profitable, bloody headlines, reporters have shown up in droves. Alongside conflict-riddled stories, police violence has fertilized what has become an international movement.</p><p>Perhaps the way police violence energizes protests is most obvious at <a href=\"http://www.occupyoakland.org/\">Occupy Oakland</a>. Law enforcement’s attacks against protestors resulted in a great deal of harm, most prominently the critical injury of veteran Scott Olsen who suffered from a fractured skull and brain swelling after being hit by a police projectile.</p><p>Rather than retreating from the threat, Oakland’s occupiers showed up in droves the following day and called for a General Strike on Wednesday, Nov. 2. Cities throughout the world are organizing solidarity demonstrations.</p><p>According to a <a href=\"http://www.occupytogether.org/actions/\">Meetup map</a> on the <a href=\"http://www.occupytogether.org/\">Occupy Together</a> website, there are 2,252 cities involved in Occupy actions, as of the writing of this article. In many of these cities, protestors are engaged in 24/7 demonstrations, some of which have lasted more than a month. Each week new occupations emerge and join an internationally connected, decentralized movement.</p><p>The various occupations have not lacked discord. On the ground, Occupy Wall Street protests have generated heated debate in General Assemblies, meetings where people gather to strategize and make group decisions. In many cases the results are predictably messy.</p><p><a href=\"http://occupydenver.org/\">Occupy Denver</a> has found itself endlessly debating the virtues of employing a diversity of tactics versus nonviolence. Protestors have endlessly accused each other of being feds, agent provocateurs and snitches. Debates from General Assemblies have leaked onto Twitter.</p><p>Charges of racism and patriarchy have been waged at <a href=\"http://occupylosangeles.org/\">Occupy Los Angeles</a> by <a href=\"http://unpermittedla.wordpress.com/2011/10/16/statement-from-decolonize-la/\">Decolonize Los Angeles</a>, an organization that split from the original group. Bickering between people who spend the night at occupations and others who go home to warm beds creates tensions between demonstrators. Mainstream media, such as <a href=\"http://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/01/us/dissenting-or-seeking-shelter-homeless-stake-a-claim-at-protests.html?_r=1&amp;scp=1&amp;sq=occupy%20wall%20street%20homeless&amp;st=cse\"><em>The New York Times</em></a>, has caught onto rifts among people with and without homes, while they are attempting to share space in the demonstrations.</p><p>Despite internal strife, inclement weather and police violence, numbers in the streets grow. &nbsp;Media coverage continues to build. The Occupy Movement has generated significant noise and has forced mainstream media to examine questions of economic inequity. The public pays attention, not because of consistent or clear movement messaging, but because the media look when protestors bleed.</p><p>When police in Oakland, Denver, <a href=\"http://occupyatlanta.org/\">Atlanta</a>, <a href=\"http://occupynashville.org/\">Nashville</a>, New York City, <a href=\"http://occupyportland.org/\">Portland</a> and beyond repress dissent with violence, all eyes turn toward the protests. Public sympathy builds. Numbers increase.</p><p>Law enforcement has forgotten the lessons it has learned when Connor’s attacks backfired and the protestors’ won. By attacking the Occupy Wall Street Movement, the police once again aid an uprising and fan the flames of dissent.</p><p><strong>--Kyle Harris</strong></p><p><em>Kyle Harris is an editor at <a href=\"http://theprecarious.com\">The Precarious</a>, Co-Producer at <a href=\"http://improbablepictures.com\">Improbable Pictures</a>, and author of the blog <a href=\"http://queerradical.com\">Queer Radical</a>. &nbsp;</em></p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_revision_body` VALUES ('node','article',0,13,13,'und',0,'<p>Cassandra Lewis is on the streets, yelling at the big banks. The bankers are trying to take her family home, and she is angry.</p><p>&nbsp;She is not alone.</p><p>&nbsp;“I won’t give up,” Lewis said. “You don’t let them push you. I try to tell people it’s not an embarrassment, it’s an epidemic.”</p><p>The 58-year-old Denver resident was one of a handful of homeowners who participated in the <a href=\"http://progressivecoalition.org/\">Colorado Progressive Coalition’s</a> Mile High Showdown in October. The week of actions targeted Wells Fargo’s lending practices with increasingly intense protests.</p><p>The CPC began focusing on foreclosure issues about a year ago, organizing director Ben Hanna said. A lot of their work has been talking to homeowners, bringing them together and helping them support each other. Over the next several weeks, The Precarious will share the stories of some of these homeowners.</p><p>&nbsp;“It’s a full time job trying to deal with banks on their own,” Hanna said. “Just being able to get into a room with 30 other people who are going through same thing, a lot of that personal shame gets washed away. People realize it’s not them.”</p><p>Fifteen-year-old Dravell Ross has seen the threat of foreclosure strain his family for several years. The Overland High School sophomore sat quietly as the first day of action began. This was not Dravell’s first protest. He previously marched into a bank with a group supporting a family seeking loan modification. He’s not sure if they changed anything, but it felt good to try to help.</p><p>The group of a little more than a dozen people was sedate as each person summarized their beef with big banks in a few words. They discussed their plan to march to Wells Fargo to deliver a letter of complaint to officials.</p><p>On Tuesday, a slightly larger group gathered to deliver 300 notes from customers pledging to close Wells Fargo accounts.</p><p>“Hey, Wells Fargo, you’re no good, you ripped off our neighborhood,” they chanted, but they were still mannerly enough to stop at every orange crosswalk hand and carefully straighten a rug they displaced inside the bank.</p><p>By Thursday, the protesters, led by the Colorado Progressive Coalition, had multiplied to approximately 50. &nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;“Today, we’re moving in,” Hanna said, revving up the protesters before the march. The crowd brought pillows, teddy bears, house plants and mops, the idea being that if Wells Fargo took houses through foreclosure, then they’d symbolically turn the shiny bank lobby into a cozy living room.</p><p>When they got to the bank at the corner of 17<sup>th</sup> Street and Broadway at about 2 p.m., it was locked. &nbsp;“Attention Customers!!” a note on the door read. “We are unexpectedly closed due to an emergency and will reopen as soon as possible.”</p><p>Save a few Denver Police and Wells Fargo employees, the bank was empty.</p><p>Most of the protesters crammed into an outer vestibule, where they rattled the glass wall between themselves and the police and bankers. A young man in tan sneaked in through a side door to try and let fellow protesters in. He was dragged away by police.</p><p>The crowd left the little anteroom after a few minutes, and marched around a sofa, table and chairs set on the sidewalk. Three men stayed inside, sticking notes like “That’s right. Fucking hide behind closed doors” and “Where is our bailout?” to the inner doors.</p><p>It was about an hour before police – who included eight officers in riot gear – asked the protesters to leave so the bank could reopen.</p><p>“The first thing we take into consideration is the safety of our customers and our team members,” said Cristie Drumm about the afternoon shutdown. She’s Wells Fargo’s vice president for communications for Colorado, and she sounded the part: extremely polite and ready to deploy a slew of numbers in the bank’s favor before she was even asked how long the bank was closed (about an hour, between 2 and 3 p.m.)</p><p>What are Drumm’s numbers? Since 2009, Wells Fargo has modified 716,000 mortgages, and that number grows daily. They’ve forgiven $4 billion in loan principal.&nbsp; They continue to lend, and as of Sept. 30 have made $760 billion in loans.</p><p>Hanna has his own set of numbers, including the fact that at the end of 2009, Wells Fargo had modified only 22 percent of eligible loans. The Federal Reserve Board fined the bank $85 million for getting people into inappropriate loans. Wells Fargo is responsible for many of the more than 2,000 Denver homes in foreclosure.</p><p>Lewis seems less concerned with warring numbers than with the things that seem like obvious disparities to her. Her story, which will be reported in coming weeks, is complex. She has never lagged in house payments, but her family home may be lost because of a shaky deal made to keep the house after her cousin she rented to fell behind on the mortgage by a couple of months.</p><p>Lewis is angry that people with so much money are spending their time squabbling over her small two-bedroom home on the east side of Denver. But if they keep fighting, so will she.</p><p>“This is our home,” she said.</p><p><strong>--Leslie Wilber</strong></p><p><em>Leslie Wilber is a journalist who has covered legal issues, police misconduct, high school sports and various other disastrous things. She\'s currently an editor at <a href=\"http://theprecarious.com\">The Precarious</a>.&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</em></p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_revision_body` VALUES ('node','article',0,14,14,'und',0,'<p>There are many ways to fight home foreclosure: phone calls, letters, meetings with housing counselors, and direct actions.</p><p>Leonard McWilliams has tried them all.</p><p>The 56-year-old is no closer to finding a way to keep his family in their house. In fact, he’s contemplating another week of bad news. The real estate agent who was trying to sell the house dropped McWilliams. She told him it was because he sought to restructure his mortgage. Of course, trying to sell the house was a condition for restructuring.</p><p>Then came the mail from Owen Loan Services, the most recent in a line of four companies to hold the mortgage. The multi-page letter lying on the dining room table offers no solutions, just a hike to $2,144.28 monthly payments. That eats up all but $900 of his Veterans Administration pension check<ins cite=\"mailto:K%20A\" datetime=\"2011-11-01T13:32\">, </ins>his only income for raising two teenage boys.&nbsp;</p><p>At that rate, McWilliams cannot afford the ranch-style house, packed with colorful art projects he and his boys have created from discarded furniture and scrap wood. The best solution might be giving up, moving into a small, cheap apartment: <ins cite=\"mailto:K%20A\" datetime=\"2011-11-01T13:33\">T</ins>hat would stop the uncertainty and the fear.</p><p>“We’ve fought for so long,” he says. “It’s our home, and it should be worth fighting for.”</p><p>Desperation drove McWilliam’s family to the four-bedroom house in the southeast suburb of Denver. In 2004, he was raising his two sons and caring for foster children. The family lived in Denver’s City Park neighborhood. McWilliams’ own mother lived nearby, convenient support for the single father.</p><p>McWilliams was working on a Ph<ins cite=\"mailto:K%20A\" datetime=\"2011-11-01T13:34\">.</ins>D<ins cite=\"mailto:K%20A\" datetime=\"2011-11-01T13:34\">.</ins> at the time. A stress-related string of health problems led to a fall down a flight of stairs in the multi-level Victorian home. McWilliams spent a large portion of 2005 in hospitals and nursing homes. Back at his house, he needed to sit and scoot up stairs to travel from floor to floor.</p><p>“That was my day, mostly,” he says. “Trying to get up and down stairs.”</p><p>McWilliams needed a house where everything was on one floor. He needed to be as close as possible to family. He needed to move fast.</p><p>In retrospect, McWilliams says, those factors helped the realtor sell him a house he couldn’t afford.</p><p>&nbsp;“He preyed on our desperation,” McWilliams says.</p><p>When trying to qualify McWilliams for loans<ins cite=\"mailto:K%20A\" datetime=\"2011-11-01T13:34\">,</ins> the agent included McWilliams’ spotty income from foster care. He based the estimated income on two children per bedroom – which could have been up to six foster children, a total of eight kids – living in McWilliams’ current home.&nbsp; The realtor pushed for McWilliams to look at an even larger home, priced around $400,000.</p><p>McWilliams put on the brakes.</p><p>“I knew there had to be a limit,” he says. The asking price for the home he bought was about $220,000. “It seemed like it was reasonable.”</p><p>He signed on for an adjustable rate mortgage, with starting payments of $1,200 a month. In less than a year, McWilliams was in trouble.</p><p>“That was almost right away,” he says. “We didn’t get the projected foster children.”</p><p>Then the mortgage adjusted, rising faster and higher than McWilliams had been led to believe it would. Soon he was behind in payments and at risk for foreclosure.</p><p>Like many others at risk of losing their homes, McWilliams has spent years trying to find the right combination of letters and phone calls that would lead to a manageable deal with his mortgage company. He’s consulted housing conselors. His family has worked with advocacy groups and with the help of <a href=\"http://www.acorn.org/\">ACORN</a> wrapped his home in a human chain to stall foreclosure. He’s now one of roughly 50 families working with the <a href=\"http://progressivecoalition.org/\">Colorado Progressive Coalition</a> to save their own homes and the homes of others, says Ben Hannah, the organizing director with that group.</p><p>McWilliams points out a few positives have come with this turmoil. His children have learned about political organizing. Dravell Ross, his 15-year-old son, says attending protests at banks to help others keep their houses feels good, if not always effective.</p><p>But years of instability have&nbsp;stressed the family, McWilliams says. &nbsp;Dravell agrees. The Overland High School sophomore understands if his family moves, they might have little or no notice.</p><p>“You never know when it’s going to come,” Dravell says. “You have to be on your toes. You need to be ready to say goodbye to your friends, say goodbye to your neighbors.”</p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_revision_body` VALUES ('node','article',0,15,15,'und',0,'<p>Frustrated by paying fees to big banks, entrepreneur Kristen Christian got fed up. She decided to take action, withdraw her money from big banks and reinvest it in local banks and credit unions—and she has called on others to do the same.</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://media.cutimes.com/cutimes/article/2011/10/17/Christian,Kristen-resize-328x400.jpg\" style=\"float: left; width: 150px; height: 150px; \">She has organized <a href=\"http://banktransferday.com\">Bank Transfer Day</a>. On November 5 over 70,000 people around the country have pledged to withdraw their money from big banks and join her in reinvesting in local banks and credit unions.</p><p>“I was tired of paying outrageous fees to banks for a severe lack of services. I was tired of having money access determined by a corporation and the final straw came with the announcement of new monthly fees for any customers with less than $20,000 in combined accounts. It’s apparent this new policy directly targets the impoverished and working class,”</p><p>Bank Transfer Day shares hacker collective <a href=\"http://anonops.blogspot.com/\">Anonymous</a>’ use of <a href=\"http://eddiecolla.wordpress.com/\">Eddie Colla</a>’s Guy Fawkes imagery, also associated with the <a href=\"http://www.occupytogether.org/\">Occupy Wall Street </a>protests. Christian planned actions on November 5, the date of the failed Gunpowder Plot of 1605.</p><p>Despite sharing imagery and similar targets, Christian distances herself from both Occupy Wall Street and Anonymous. According to a recent press release, “The goal of Bank Transfer Day is to enrich communities rather than disrupt them.”&nbsp;</p><p><strong>--Kyle Harris</strong></p><p><em>Kyle Harris is an editor at <a href=\"http://theprecarious.com\">The Precarious</a>, Co-Producer at <a href=\"http://improbablepictures.com\">Improbable Pictures</a>, and author of the blog <a href=\"http://queerradical.com\">Queer Radical</a>. &nbsp;</em></p><p>&nbsp;</p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_revision_body` VALUES ('node','article',0,16,16,'und',0,'<p>In her newest book, <em><a href=\"http://cantankeroustitles.com/books/cambodian-grrrl\">Cambodian Grrrl: Self-Publishing in Phnom Penh</a>, </em>Anne Elizabeth Moore narrates a series of self-publishing workshops she recently conducted with students at a Cambodian women’s university. With cynicism and wonder, she escorts readers through the troubling history of Cambodia and her humorous attempt to inspire women to create zines.</p><p>Whether wandering the killing fields, where Pol Pot’s regime slaughtered hundreds or hand washing her underwear, her candid observations of history, politics, and do-it-yourself living relish the enormous class and cultural disparities between the United States and Cambodia.</p><p>Moore bridges this chasm by celebrating the vital power of creating media. She demonstrates the importance of storytelling, the creative process, and genuine inventiveness as she struggles to communicate across language and cultural gaps. Using zine-making, she creates a vibrant context for intercultural dialogue and friendship.</p><p>As the former editor of <a href=\"http://www.punkplanet.com/\"><em>Punk Planet</em></a> and the author of <a href=\"http://thenewpress.com/index.php?option=com_title&amp;task=view_title&amp;metaproductid=1662\"><em>Unmarketable</em></a>, Moore has been a major force shaping D.I.Y. ethics in the United States. Bringing her vast experience as a publisher, editor, writer, and educator to a classroom bubbling over with the effervescent energy of 30 giggling Cambodian women, she finds herself moved by their happiness and troubled by their lack of knowledge about Cambodia’s past.</p><p>She describes the post-traumatic stress disorder pervasive in people 30 and older and the haunting silence shielding younger people from the memory of the Khmer Rouge.&nbsp; Creating zines with the women, Moore cultivates opportunities for her students to address the country’s violent history, contemplate gender and build confidence to challenge the nation’s failure to incorporate women into positions of power.</p><p>United States’ violence shaped the history of Cambodia and is a significant barrier in building relationships. Moore does not recount to her students the U.S. bombings that led to Pol Pot’s rise to power and the landmines planted by the U.S. military. She describes the embarrassment in omitting historical details that might compromise her friendships with the women.</p><p>For Moore, making zines allows people to bear witness to experiences often erased by government, family, and corporate pressures. <em>Cambodian Grrrl</em> challenges readers to be inventive, to create, and to engage as deeply with our histories, culture, and geography as we do our own personal lives and experiences.</p><p>Moore describes challenging her students: “To expound on topics that had not first been dictated-not by me, not by teachers, not by their government. To consider anything in their paths worthy of engagement.” Ultimately her demand for eager awareness reminds readers why inventing, writing, and self-publishing might allow us to survive. These practices force us to connect, to engage, and to remember.&nbsp;</p><p><strong>--Kyle Harris</strong></p><p><em>Kyle Harris is an editor at <a href=\"http://theprecarious.com\">The Precarious</a>, Co-Producer at <a href=\"http://improbablepictures.com\">Improbable Pictures</a>, and author of the blog <a href=\"http://queerradical.com\">Queer Radical</a>. &nbsp;</em></p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_revision_body` VALUES ('node','article',0,17,17,'und',0,'<p><a href=\"http://theprecarious.com\"><em>The Precarious</em></a>. On its face, the name doesn’t offer much optimism or hope for longevity.</p><p>So why call an online magazine – one we want to have a long, useful life – <a href=\"http://theprecarious.com\"><em>The Precarious</em></a>?&nbsp; This is a precarious moment.&nbsp; Foreclosure, eviction, unemployment and imprisonment are epidemic. Too often, even the employed teeter on the edge of stability, working part-time or on contract, lacking healthcare or a living wage.</p><p>Shit is fertilizer; it’s an old and obvious truth. And although much is dire, new possibilities grow from this precarity. Community bonds strengthen. Creativity and ingenuity arise. People take to the streets, risking jobs and safety to occupy cities worldwide.</p><p>There’s a lot to be alarmed about; just ask corporate media – they’ll happily serve your daily allotment of gore and horror. But we’re more interested in how people survive than how they might die. We look forward to sharing stories that address the instabilities defining our era and the inspirational solutions everyone can create.</p><p>In these next few weeks we will tell stories about people whose homes have been foreclosed, who have taken direct action against banks, who have defaulted on student loans, who have left the comfort of their homes to sleep in the streets and to occupy cities across this country.</p><p>We will review books, art, music and literature, discuss the politics of sports and entertainment, debate pressing social and political issues, and offer suggestions about how to improve our relationships, transportation, sex, cooking and more.</p><p>We look forward to building our content with you.</p><p>Shoot us an <a href=\"mailto:info@theprecarious.com?subject=From%20the%20Website&amp;body=This%20is%20from%20the%20website.\">email</a>. Let us know what stories you want to read about. Tell us how we can improve. And let us know you are out there.</p><p>With Love and Enthusiasm,</p><p>The Precarious Editors</p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_revision_body` VALUES ('node','article',0,18,18,'und',0,'<p>DENVER ­- Virginia Salazar has mastered the image of great-grandmotherly goodness. She crochets blankets. She presses her well-wishes and prayers on folks in tough spots. On Tuesday nights, she makes dinner for her two grown daughters, even though she doesn’t like to cook.&nbsp; They help her around the house.</p><p>Then, on Wednesday afternoons, Salazar picks up a small camera bag and puts on a neon vest with “Stop Police Brutality” printed on the back in big, black letters. The 83-year-old woman stands in Denver’s Civic Center Park, a tiny, white-haired scarecrow against law enforcement. Salazar began attending Food Not Bombs meals weekly in 2008, as part of her regular duties with Denver CopWatch.</p><p>“I’ve never had problems with the police, nor my family,” 83-year-old Salazar says. But when friends started Denver CopWatch in 2000, Salazar was frustrated with reports of police abuse and misconduct. She joined the group in hopes of bringing peace to the city she’s lived in since 1950.</p><p>CopWatch records interactions with police on the streets, at events like Food Not Bombs, and at protests to provide evidence of – and hopefully deter – police brutality and misconduct.</p><p>&nbsp;“It’s bad enough they do what they do,” says Salazar, describing her feelings about police brutality. “But they get away with it. I don’t like violence.”</p><p>In fact, Salazar says, she doesn’t even like to see gristlier reports on the news. When she describes police roughness she’s seen, she cringes. Some of her worst memories of police are from the 2008 Democratic National Convention.</p><p>“They were dressed for combat,” Salazar says. “It was horrible. The whole world is watching and you’re at war.”</p><p>Although Denver CopWatch receives fewer complaints from residents than in the past, Salazar can list plenty of reasons not to trust the city’s police. Accusations of violence continue.</p><p>Misconduct accusations can be expensive: the Denver city council already has approved more than $1 million in settlements in police brutality cases this year.&nbsp; More recently, there’s the pending reinstatement of two officers who were recorded beating a man in Lower Downtown. The possibility those men could patrol the streets again makes Salazar angry: It gives police the idea they can do whatever they want, she says.</p><p>&nbsp;“They don’t intimidate me one bit,” Salazar says.</p><p>Salazar is popular at the Wednesday meals, not only because she and other CopWatch volunteers seem to keep police away. She checks in on regulars’ health. Her vest invites the occasional personal story about police brutality. On a recent Wednesday, a man from Oklahoma told her about being attacked by police dogs while officers searched for another man. Salazar winced as he pulled up his pants leg to show off the scar.</p><p>Among the homeless, the hungry, the punks and the traveling folks at the park, stories of unpleasant brushes with the law are common.</p><p>It’s part of what keeps Salazar coming back. “These people are vulnerable and the cops pick on them,” she says.</p><p><strong>--Leslie Wilber</strong></p><p><em>Leslie Wilber is a journalist who has covered legal issues, police&nbsp;misconduct, high school sports and various other disastrous things.&nbsp;She\'s currently an editor at <a href=\"http://theprecarious.com\">The Precarious</a>.</em></p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_revision_body` VALUES ('node','article',0,19,19,'und',0,'<p>Wandering through golden, trembling aspen groves, trudging up a rocky trail through Mt. Evans National Forest towards Hell’s Hole, a circle of two-thousand-year-old bristlecone pine trees surrounded by alpine willow, I’m about as far removed from debates about political theory and movement building as possible. This landscape buffers me from Denver’s burned-out, post-activist critics backbiting the Occupy Wall Street protestors, one day after New York’s finest arrested dozens of the demonstrators. I enjoy the respite.</p><p>I’m grateful for the rare opportunity to spend my afternoon with trembling aspens and bristlecone pines. Aspen trees are part of clonal colonies,&nbsp;where a horizontal network of roots, some lasting as long as 80 thousand years, sprout new shoots, trees that can last between 40 and 150 years. The bristlecone pine trees are the world’s oldest single organisms, some living nearly five thousand years. These old trees have seen it all.</p><p>Unable to let go of the rants and critiques aimed at the newest social movement players who suffer in jail as I hike, I can’t help but think how fast people burn out, how quickly the flames of passion smolder into ash. I realize those of us in social movements have a lot to learn from these old trees. Our movements’ resilience and impact depends on these lessons.</p><p>From the aspens, we can learn to understand movement as a larger, connected, deeply rooted, horizontal force that bonds individuals, relationships, and specific organizations and actions. Like the resilient aspen, we function as a collective organism. Our roots and power are underground and safe from repression. Our networks feed new manifestations of radical, autonomous, and collective desires. If a few trees are chopped down, the organism survives.</p><p>We can learn about perseverance from the bristlecone pine. These ancient, wizened trees remind us that slow growth facilitates survival. These trees live in brutal climates, just below tree line, where they weather cold, harsh winds, dry soil, and a short growing season. Though they rarely reproduce and regenerate, they survive by growing slowly and steadily over time.</p><p>The bristlecone pines remind me of the lesson of the tortoise and the hare. Slow and steady wins the race. In our era of multitasking, global relationships, and never-ending deadlines, it’s easy to forget the value of taking our time. Long after millions of trees, flowers, and animals have come and gone, the bristlecone pines remain standing. Our quest for justice goes back thousands of years too. Our movement’s lineage is long.&nbsp;</p><p><strong>--Kyle Harris</strong></p><p>Kyle Harris is an editor at <a href=\"http://theprecarious.com\">The Precarious</a>, Co-Producer at <a href=\"http://improbablepictures.com\">Improbable Pictures</a>, and author of the blog <a href=\"http://queerradical.com\">Queer Radical</a>. &nbsp;</p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_revision_body` VALUES ('node','article',0,21,21,'und',0,'<p>All over the world, people are taking over their cities, shutting down banks, attacking military infrastructure, risking life and limb fighting for a better life and a healthy eco-system. Here at <a href=\"http://theprecarious.com\">The </a><a>Precarious</a>, we’re going to do a quick week-in-review of some of our favorite actions around the world.</p><p>The highlight of this past week was <a href=\"http://www.occupyoakland.org/\">Occupy Oakland’s</a> General Strike. After last week’s brutal attack on their Occupy encampment where police projectiles fractured veteran Scott Olsen’s skull, tens of thousands skipped work and hit the streets. Seven thousand shut down the Oakland ports, while others blockaded Chase and Wells Fargo banks. Bank branches and Whole Foods windows were shattered and several hundred people occupied the abandoned Travelers’ Aid Building.&nbsp;</p><p>In <a href=\"http://www.occupytogether.org/2011/11/03/the-occupations-report-1103/\">solidarity</a> with Occupy Oakland, approximately 500 Chicago students walked out of their classes and Lawrence, Kan. demonstrators held a 99 minute General Strike. In San Jose, a single construction worker has sat on top of the City Hall for over a week, while in Seattle protestors have taken over a Chase bank.</p><p>All in all, despite internal squabbles, the Occupy Movement continues to make a big explosion.</p><p>Speaking of explosions—Happy <a href=\"http://www.gunpowder-plot.org/\">Guy Fawkes Day</a>—you know, the anniversary of the 1605 Gun Powder Plot.</p><p><a href=\"http://anonops.blogspot.com/\">Anonymous</a>, the notorious hacker collective has pledged to wage Internet war on Fox, Facebook, countless banks and the Zetas drug cartel today. If that wasn’t enough to make the mighty <a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/Nov.Fifth\">Bank Transfer Day</a>—a day where over 70,000 have committed to shifting their bank accounts from big banks such as Bank of America and Chase to local credit unions. Kudos.</p><p>People in power are shaking in their boots and things are heating up. Speaking of a rise in temperatures, global warming skeptic <a href=\"http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052970204422404576594872796327348.html\">Richard Muller</a> has joined the National Academy of Science and the vast majority of scientific scholars in admitting the obvious: Global warming is real.</p><p>We continue to be inspired by the resilience of the <a href=\"http://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/04/world/middleeast/7-killed-in-syria-despite-deal-to-halt-violence.html?_r=1&amp;scp=1&amp;sq=syrian&amp;st=cse\">Syrian uprising</a> and the bravery of thousands who continue to demonstrate in the streets despite tens of thousands being murdered by the regime of Bashar Al-Assad. We mourn the loss of nun <a href=\"http://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/04/world/asia/tibetan-nun-dies-in-self-immolation.html?scp=1&amp;sq=nun%20tibet&amp;st=cse\">Qiu Xiang</a>, the latest Tibetan to set herself on fire and die while demanding the return of the Dalai Lama and an expansion of religious freedom under Chinese rule.</p><p>It’s been a week of passion and social action. People are fighting hard for what they believe. We continue to be inspired by all involved in struggle and creation.</p><p>If you have stories you want us to report next Saturday, November 12, feel free to get in touch. <a href=\"mailto:kyle@theprecarious.com?subject=Saturday%20Recap&amp;body=Here%20are%20my%20ideas%20for%20the%20Saturday%20Recap%21\">Email us here</a>. Until then, happy liberation!&nbsp;</p><div><div><div id=\"_com_1\" uage=\"JavaScript\"><p><strong>--Kyle Harris</strong></p><p><em>Kyle Harris is an editor at <a href=\"http://theprecarious.com\">The Precarious</a>, Co-Producer at <a href=\"http://improbablepictures.com\">Improbable Pictures</a>, and author of the blog <a href=\"http://queerradical.com\">Queer Radical</a>. &nbsp;</em></p></div></div></div><p>&nbsp;</p>','','filtered_html');
