INSERT INTO `field_revision_body` VALUES ('node','article',0,28,28,'und',0,'<p>Cassandra Lewis builds up a preacher’s steam as she stands in her living room, talking about her faith and her fight against banks.</p><p>The big banks have taken Lewis’ mother’s home. Her friends’ homes. Now the banks are trying to take her home.</p><p>But they cannot bully a 58-year-old black woman who grew up in Birmingham, Alabama during the Civil Rights Movement</p><p>“If I give up, that means I gave up on God,” Lewis says. “Like he had a ram in the bush for Abraham, he has this ram for me.”</p><p>If there’s a typical route to home foreclosure, it is not Lewis’ story.</p><p>“This is a very complicated case, this house is,” Lewis says, laughing. Even when she talks about the possibility of losing her home, Lewis laughs and smiles a lot. But don’t mistake that gaiety for a lack of determination; she has fought for years, chronicling every step she’s taken.</p><p>Stories of home foreclosures often can be told in giant stacks of paperwork. Lewis carried the letters, contracts and court documents in a blue shopping bag for months She took them to work. She took them to the store. She even brought them to church, because she couldn’t bear to think that if her car was stolen, her paperwork would be lost.</p><p>She didn’t let the bag out of her site until she delivered it to a lawyer, who’s taken her case pro bono.</p><p>Lewis’ daughter bought the house 18 years ago. In 1999, the daughter moved to Las Vegas, and since then, Lewis and various other family members have lived in the house. The trouble started in 2006, when a cousin lived there, and got behind in payments by a couple of months. Lewis’ daughter got several letters from a company with a seemingly self-explanatory name: Keep Your Home Solutions.</p><p>Her daughter drew up a contract with the company: If the family kept up mortgage payments for two years, the home would revert fully to their ownership. No worries.</p><p>But there was a catch: While Lewis and her family were faithfully making payments to Keep Your Home Solutions, the company sold the house to Brian D. John.</p><p>John used equity in the house to take out a loan. His failure to keep up those payments has led to pain and harassment for Lewis.</p><p>The documentation Lewis didn’t give to lawyers remains in her home. She keeps recordings of daily phone calls from an employee of a real estate agency, offering her cash for keys to her house. Lewis has two years’ worth of date books in which she’s noted every time the same real estate agent came to her home The visits became so frequent she began sleeping on her couch near the front door, fully clothed, dreading the day deputies would drag her from her home.</p><p>This type of stress is typical for people facing imminent foreclosure, says Ben Hanna, organizing director at the Colorado Progressive Coalition. The coalition has been working with homeowners to stop foreclosure for about a year, and in October organized a week of actions against big banks’ lending practices.</p><p>“Can you imagine living month to month with a foreclosure sales date?” Hanna says. “And then a month out, it changes?”</p><p>Lewis says the feeling is like something out of a horror movie.</p><p>“I can’t even describe it,” she says. “Although these are just material things, you believe in God, but it makes you feel like you want to kill yourself. I see this and it’s like they’re trying to take a person’s heart out.”</p><p>The closest Lewis has come to eviction was last year, when her house was up for auction at the courthouse.&nbsp; By chance, nobody bid. A judge has since ruled the home cannot be sold until issues surrounding the ownership are cleared up.</p><p>Lewis sleeps a little easier, in her bedroom. But she still checks her front door every day to see if any court papers have been served.</p><p>While fighting for her own home, Lewis has been encouraged to help others keep their houses. She volunteers at CPC’s actions against banks, and at protests cheers louder than most others in the crowd.</p><p>“I won’t give up,” Lewis says. “We have got to get the word out.”</p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_revision_body` VALUES ('node','article',0,29,29,'und',0,'<blockquote><p>Dear Queer Radical,</p><div style=\"background-color: transparent; \"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; \">My friend and collaborator is a 33-year-old mother of five and in an open relationship with her husband. We were at a social movement conference and Mommy wound up sleeping with a younger guy, probably nineteen or twenty. As a fellow mother (though monogamous), I called her out. If she were a guy hitting on a younger woman, nobody would put up with that shit. Now she’s pissed at me. Did I do the right thing? </span><br><br><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; \">Monogomous Mary</span><br><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; \">Austin, TX</span><br><br>&nbsp;</div></blockquote><div style=\"background-color: transparent; \"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; \">Dear Monogamous Mary,</span><br><br><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; \">Seriously, you’re asking Queer Radical if you did the right thing? When I was 20 I was running around bathhouses sucking 60-year-old cocks and loving every inch of them. I adored those guys and am grateful to this day for all I learned. If someone had called them out for being “fucked up,” it would have stripped me of my hard-won autonomy and pleasure. I did what I wanted, with whom I wanted, assuming they wanted it too. </span><br><br><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; \">My guess is that your 19-year-old boy was thrilled to be sleeping with your mommy friend. You don’t indicate he was uncomfortable with it. You don’t indicate he didn’t like it. You don’t indicate he didn’t initiate it.</span><br><br><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; \">If he wants Mommy and Mommy wants him, there is no problem. It’s consensual sex, plain and simple.</span><br><br><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; \">Be real. You’re not only fronting sex-negativity; you’re also acting Mom-negative. If you want to support parents in social movements, allow them room to embrace the fullness of their beings. It’s the least you can do to support their role in our collective liberation.</span><br><br><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; \">You’re pissy because your friend’s getting laid and you’re so full of resentment, you can’t enjoy your own sexuality. Jerk off. Go fuck. Open up your relationship. Do whatever it takes to satisfy yourself so that you behave kindly to your friend. Bonds between mothers and collaborators matter.</span><br><br><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; \">Don’t give me some half-baked argument about age and consent that strips away a younger person’s agency. And certainly don’t act like everybody would be pissed off if a younger woman and an older man were sleeping together. I support consenting adults fucking. So do a lot of people who don’t hate sexuality.</span><br><br><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; \">We all have a right to decide what we want to do with our own and other consenting adults’ bodies. It’s a basic feminist principle.</span><br><br><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; \">Newsflash: Young people have brains and use them.</span><br><br><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; \">Mutual aid, mutual pleasure, and mutual masturbation: these are social movements in action. Consensus reached?</span><br><br><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; \">Go apologize now. </span><br><br><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; \">Sans Solidarity,</span><br><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; \">Queer Radical</span></div>','Dear Queer Radical:   My friend and collaborator is a 33-year-old mother of five and in an open relationship with her husband. We were at a social movement conference and Mommy wound up sleeping with a younger guy','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_revision_body` VALUES ('node','article',0,30,30,'und',0,'<p>There are phone book worth of reasons the Mississippi personhood ballot measure lacks merit. The initiative – which voters will consider today – defines personhood as beginning at conception.</p><p>Sperm, meet Egg. Congratulations! You’re a person now.</p><p>Pro-choice and women’s health advocates have rallied against the Personhood Amendment, and rightfully so. As written, it seems designed to limit access to some birth control, stem-cell research and its obvious target, abortion.</p><p>Ah, abortion. That’s where debate always gets sticky.</p><p>Most critiques of Amendment 26 include a phrase that goes like this: the Personhood Amendment bans abortion, even in cases of rape or incest. Some, generously, will add the concern of risk to a potential mother’s life. This problematic language gets thrown into the abortion debate a lot in order to convince – wait, who?</p><p>For those who think life begins at conception, the embryo is a life, no matter how it’s begotten. In fact, PersonhoodMississippi.com answers the “what about abortion?” question by linking to<a href=\"http://www.rebeccakiessling.com/\"> Rebecca Kiessling’s website</a>.&nbsp;Kiessling is a radically pro-life speaker whose primary mission seems to be encouraging rape victims not to abort – after all, her own life is a result of rape.&nbsp; So that camp might feel sympathy for a pregnant rape victim, but by their logic, she is still a murderer if she refuses to incubate that cellular clump of person.</p><p>An important component of pro-choice arguments is that people can make reasonable decisions about their health, their bodies and their lives. So pregnant women can decide to abort whether their birth control failed, they were raped, they lost their jobs, they were victims of incest, their partner is no longer supportive and they don’t wish to parent alone – or even if they just don’t want to buy maternity jeans with the stretchy front panel. The circumstances shouldn’t make a difference.</p><p>But surely, there are people on the fence. People who think abortion might be OK if - if what? If the potential mother has suffered something horrible? If she has no other choice but to die?</p><p>Let’s stipulate that when you add rape, incest or life-or-death medical decisions to any circumstance, you make it worse: child abuse, a burglary, work, pregnancy, dating. Naturally, these factors are a layer of trauma atop the decision to abort or not. People dealing with these issues should have every tool available for dealing with pregnancy. &nbsp;As should everyone else facing an unwanted pregnancy.</p><p>Arguments that we must specially allow for abortion in cases of rape, incest or if a pregnancy is life-threatening weaken the pro-choice viewpoint. They grind away at the legitimate claim that people should be able to end pregnancies for any reason.</p><p>Too often in discussions of debates framed as women’s issues, deference is given to those who can easily be painted as innocent victims. There is support for a woman, so long as that support comes in the form of protective aid. That notion alone insults women trying to make the best choices for themselves and their families.</p><p>But it also implies there is something shameful, something less valid about abortions that aren’t the result of violence or life-threatening ailments.&nbsp; Dragging out the “even in cases of rape or incest” language, creates a hierarchy of good abortions (Under duress! Unforeseeable conditions!) vs. bad abortions (Slutty sex! Poor people making bad choices!)</p><p>This line of rhetoric does nothing to improve abortion’s image as the reasonable and personal medical decision that it is.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>-- <em>Leslie Wilber is a journalist who has covered legal issues, police misconduct, high school sports and various other disastrous things. She\'s currently an editor at The Precarious.</em></p><p>&nbsp;</p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_revision_body` VALUES ('node','article',0,31,31,'und',0,'<p>Notorious Bavarian filmmaker, <a href=\"http://www.wernerherzog.com/\">Werner Herzog</a> returns to the screen this winter with <a href=\"http://www.wernerherzog.com/114.html\"><em>Into the Abyss - A Tale of Death, A Tale of Life</em></a>, a meditation on capital punishment in the United States.&nbsp; Herzog offers an expertly crafted, startlingly intimate portrait of two young men: one serving out a life sentence, the other a death row inmate.&nbsp;</p><p>Once friends, the two men were convicted separately for their involvement in the same triple homicide. Ten years later, Michael Perry sits on death row, 8 days away from his scheduled execution. His former friend, Jason Burkett has served 10 years of a life sentence. He awaits 40 years before his first chance for parole.</p><p>Herzog exploits his knack for capturing human moments and helps his audience identify with even the most disturbing or enigmatic of subjects.&nbsp; Through thoughtful, prodding and often staged interviews, Herzog paints a complex picture of the murders, the grief of the victim’s families, and of the lives of Burkett and Perry since their convictions.&nbsp;</p><p>Famous for over-the-top editorializing, Herzog’s <i>Into the Abyss</i>&nbsp;omits his traditional voice-over narration. He opts instead to use his own off-camera comments during one of his interviews with Perry to make his position on capital punishment clear.&nbsp; “I do not have to like you,” says Herzog to a smiling Perry, “but I respect you and you are a human being, and I do not believe that human beings should be executed.”&nbsp;</p><p>While Herzog does state his personal feelings on capital punishment, the film avoids directly calling out the brutality and injustice of the U.S. criminal justice system.&nbsp; Rather, Herzog remains emotionally tied to the stories of the two young men.&nbsp; The effect is haunting, if not rallying.&nbsp;</p><p>Fresh off the success of last year’s <a href=\"http://www.wernerherzog.com/114.html\"><em>Cave of Forgotten Dreams</em></a>, Herzog makes a return to his best known and often most entertaining territory with <em>Abyss</em>: moody, character driven documentaries that ask probing, deep questions about the human experience.</p><p>Herzog has a gift for telling deeply personal human stories, and for fans of his work, <em>Into the Abyss</em> will be no disappointment.&nbsp; Newcomers on the other hand, might find his somber tone and unusual style hard to digest.&nbsp;</p><p>For those interested in a more pointed send up of the US criminal justice system, the French documentary <em>Murder on a Sunday Morning</em> (Lestrade, 2001), also a case study involving an U.S. teenage murder convict, offers a more cohesive storyline and more traditional documentary structure.&nbsp; <em>Into the Abyss</em> opens Nov. 11. &nbsp;</p><p><strong>--Erica Gleichman</strong></p><p><i>Erica Gleichman writes movie reviews for The Precarious</i><strong><em>, </em></strong><em>studied Film Studies at The University of Colorado - Denver and currently lives in San Diego, California.</em></p>','Notorious Bavarian filmmaker, Werner Herzog returns to the screen this winter with Into the Abyss - A Tale of Death, A Tale of Life, a meditation on capital punishment in the United States.  Herzog offers an expertly crafted, startlingly intimate portrait of two young men: one serving out a life sentence, the other a death row inmate. \r\n\r\nOnce friends, the two men were convicted separately for their involvement in the same triple homicide. Ten years later, Michael Perry sits on death row, 8 days away from his scheduled execution. His former friend, Jason Burkett has served 10 years of a life sentence. He awaits 40 years before his first chance for parole.\r\n','filtered_html');
