ff the success of last year’s <a href=\"http://www.wernerherzog.com/114.html\"><em>Cave of Forgotten Dreams</em></a>, Herzog makes a return to his best known and often most entertaining territory with <em>Abyss</em>: moody, character driven documentaries that ask probing, deep questions about the human experience.</p><p>Herzog has a gift for telling deeply personal human stories, and for fans of his work, <em>Into the Abyss</em> will be no disappointment.&nbsp; Newcomers on the other hand, might find his somber tone and unusual style hard to digest.&nbsp;</p><p>For those interested in a more pointed send up of the US criminal justice system, the French documentary <em>Murder on a Sunday Morning</em> (Lestrade, 2001), also a case study involving an U.S. teenage murder convict, offers a more cohesive storyline and more traditional documentary structure.&nbsp; <em>Into the Abyss</em> opens Nov. 11. &nbsp;</p><p><strong>--Erica Gleichman</strong></p><p><i>Erica Gleichman writes movie reviews for The Precarious</i><strong><em>, </em></strong><em>studied Film Studies at The University of Colorado - Denver and currently lives in San Diego, California.</em></p>','Notorious Bavarian filmmaker, Werner Herzog returns to the screen this winter with Into the Abyss - A Tale of Death, A Tale of Life, a meditation on capital punishment in the United States.  Herzog offers an expertly crafted, startlingly intimate portrait of two young men: one serving out a life sentence, the other a death row inmate. ','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_revision_body` VALUES ('node','article',0,32,33,'und',0,'<p>When it comes to debates about privacy, the notion that it’s a shield for something sinister often arises.</p><p>To assuage the worries of folks who hold this point of view I will start by saying this: I have nothing to hide. I freely admit I was sitting in my living room, eating hummus with a spoon and listening to <a href=\"http://www.npr.org/programs/talk-of-the-nation/\">Talk of the Nation</a> when I started thinking about privacy this week. On the radio, they were talking about a case &nbsp;before the Supreme Court, in which the justices will decide if it was OK for police to attach a GPS device to Antoine Jones’ Jeep and track it 24/7 for nearly a month. For all but 10 days police had no warrant to use the GPS device. &nbsp;</p><p>It’s a pretty obvious – and easy – analysis to say giving police greater ability to track people is a quick route to eroding what little protection we have against the authorities. That justices more than once<a href=\"http://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/supreme-court-worries-that-new-technology-creates-1984-scenarios/2011/11/08/gIQAbHdw2M_story.html\"> drew parallels</a> between this case and the novel “1984” speaks to the level of intrusion this represents.</p><p>As I listened to the radio, a caller told the host people with nothing to hide wouldn’t worry about this type of surveillance. &nbsp;Since then, I couldn’t help but read comments about this case that echo this sentiment. While I maintain I have nothing to hide, I worry that this is alarmingly wishful thinking.</p><p>The police perception of who is suspicious and who is not can vary widely for many reasons, most notably perhaps, race and perceived economic status.</p><p>In this case, tracking Jones’ car led police to a stash of drugs and a stack of cash.</p><p>If he didn’t have all that coke, he wouldn’t be in trouble, some argue. And to some extent, that’s true: an absence of powder-filled baggies can certainly help a person beat drug charges.</p><p>But with each examination of Fourth Amendment rights, examples of innocent people who have been bothered by police, imprisoned or fined are bound to turn up. The police don’t just investigate the guilty.</p><p>The Jones case reminds me of fallout from Arizona vs. Gant, a case heard by the Supreme Court in 2009, while I was reporting on courts in South Texas. Like Jones, Gant dealt with just how much police can snoop into our cars; the justices decided that searching a car after arrest without a warrant is not legal.</p><p>In the local court system I covered, the first case to be reconsidered because of this ruling was that of a 31-year-old man, stopped about a block from his home. &nbsp;Although he didn’t have his driver’s license on him, his girlfriend was able to bring it to the scene within moments.</p><p>Still, he was arrested and his car was searched without a warrant. In the glove compartment, there was a plastic baggie with a film of cocaine residue. He was charged with possession and put through a lot of hassle.</p><p>“Good!” said some online commenters. “Let’s not protect the guilty!”</p><p>The problem is, this man was not found guilty of any crimes. There was nothing in the car that could actually get a person high – just an empty plastic bag. Since his license was produced on the scene, he couldn’t be fined for driving without one.</p><p>In the end police could offer evidence of only one misdemeanor, the very thing he was first pulled over for: playing his radio too loud.</p><p>Essentially, he spent nine months entangled in the legal system although he had nothing to hide, except, perhaps, his taste in music.&nbsp;</p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_revision_body` VALUES ('node','article',0,33,34,'und',0,'<p>&nbsp;</p><p>Look at the image of the media truck toppled on its side by rioters. One might jump to the conclusion that the Occupy Movement got bold, that class war finally meant something and that people were outraged by the failure of corporate media.</p><p>Yeah right. This is the United States. That act of property destruction couldn’t be the product of a political riot. Activists don’t get that angry. Only one thing could cause that—sports.</p><p>Penn State fires the coach. Students riot. Schools raise tuition, states cut school budgets, the military’s poverty draft compels more youth to die overseas, corporations continue to pillage the earth, and hundreds of thousands of people lose their homes to banks. The public remains largely calm.</p><p>Why do people in the United States appear to care more about their football team than the political moment we live in?</p><p>It is easy to come to the quick assumption that people in the U.S. are stupid, lazy, disconnected and largely apathetic; however, a riot, even a sports riot, suggests something quite different. Americans feel more powerful at a sports game than at the ballot, more inspired by athletes than by politicians and activists and more loyal to coaches than to social movement elders.</p><p>Why does the appeal of sports figures trump that of U.S. politicians? Quite simply, the athletes are more inspiring. A good coach rallies team morale, pleases its fans by taking risks, coordinates bold maneuvers and never shies away from a good fight. Players serve fans by sticking to their guns and winning games.</p><p>In contrast, the political establishment thrives on betraying its fans, the voters who believed, the people allegedly represented. The representatives’ loyalty is to the wealthy and to the middle road between the richest of the rich and the richest of the middle class.</p><p>Political compromise sells out the vast majority of us, whom nobody in Washington or the boardrooms of corporations represents.</p><p>It’s not as though the joy of sports remains untouched by the malevolence of corporate interest. Corporations have found ways of compromising athletics with advertising. More horrifically, they have bought off the basic democratic concept of rule by the people.</p><p>Consider Halliburton. They will never determine who wins a ballgame. They will influence who gets elected and what policies are passed.</p><p>People rightly think they have more power eating a hotdog and doing the wave than voting, meeting with politicians and struggling for reform. Political reform is a dead end road for those aiming for social change.</p><p>What the public has forgotten, in its political disenchantment, is the power of the riot—something the politically engaged could relearn from sports fans. Perhaps one day, home foreclosures, tuition increases, and police brutality will spark riots as readily as football coach firings.</p><p><strong>--Kyle Harris</strong></p><p>Kyle Harris is an editor at <a href=\"http://theprecarious.com\">The Precarious</a>, Co-Producer at <a href=\"http://improbablepictures.com\">Improbable Pictures</a>, and author of the blog <a href=\"http://queerradical.com\">Queer Radical</a>.&nbsp;</p>','','filtered_html');
