INSERT INTO `field_revision_body` VALUES ('node','article',0,34,36,'und',0,'<p>Across the world, the Occupy uprising continues, students revolt against tuition hikes and social movements are graced with a small victory and impacted by significant loss.</p><p>Last Sunday thousands gathered around the White House protesting the <a href=\"http://green.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/11/10/keystone-pipeline-decision-could-be-delayed/?scp=3&amp;sq=keystone%20delay&amp;st=cse\">Keystone XL Pipeline</a>. Days later, Obama postponed the project until after the 2012 election.</p><p>In <a href=\"http://live.montrealgazette.com/Event/Montreal_students_protest_rising_tuition_fees\">Montreal</a> riot police confronted thousands of students, the teachers association and unions at McGill University for rising up in a General Strike against tuition increases.&nbsp; In total, approximately <a href=\"http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/up-to-200000-quebec-students-stage-massive-protest-over-tuition-hikes/article2232146/\">200,000 marched</a> in Quebec to protest tuition hikes in the province.&nbsp;</p><p>In London police feared nearly <a href=\"http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/law-and-order/8877436/Huge-police-presence-ahead-of-student-demonstration.html\">10,000 students</a> would be rioting in the streets today after tuition hikes were announced. Police responded in numbers not seen since this summer’s riots and last year’s student attacks on the Conservative Party headquarters.</p><p>In the United States, students with other priorities rioted for a different reason. Burning with rage after Penn State fired coach Joe Paterno, football fanatics fought the police, tore down traffic lights and toppled a corporate media van.</p><p>This week, the <a href=\"http://occupytogether.org\">Occupy Movement</a> incurred several losses.</p><p>Yesterday, one day after <a href=\"http://www.gogolbordello.com/\">Gogol Bordello</a> played a show for <a href=\"http://www.burlingtonfreepress.com/article/20111110/NEWS02/111110019/Breaking-Police-respond-apparent-shooting-City-Hall-Park-scene-Occupy-Burlington?odyssey=mod|breaking|text|FRONTPAGE\">Occupy Burlington</a>, a 35 year-old veteran died from a self-inflicted gunshot wound.&nbsp;</p><p>Shortly after, in <a href=\"http://gawker.com/5858608/second-fatal-shooting-near-an-occupy-protest-wont-be-good-for-pr\">Oakland</a>, another man was shot 30 feet from the Occupy Oakland encampment. The ever-shifty Mayor Jean Quan is demanding once again that protestors shut down their camp.</p><p>In <a href=\"http://www.sltrib.com/sltrib/news/52896438-78/occupy-park-protesters-pioneer.html.csp\">Salt Lake City</a>, a man died at an Occupy protest from carbon monoxide poison due to a space heater and a possible drug overdose. As winter creeps into colder states, city and state officials are confronted with the decision to eject protestors from parks, incur further deaths or allow protestors to build reasonable shelters to protect themselves from the elements.</p><p>Berkeley police beat students who were sitting on the ground, arms linked, nonviolently defending their encampment. Twenty-two students, 1 professor and 16 others were arrested at the demonstration. <a href=\"http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=%2Fc%2Fa%2F2011%2F11%2F11%2FMNH21LTC4D.DTL\">The San Francisco Chronicle</a>&nbsp;quoted Berkeley University of California Police Captain Margo Bennett, who has drawn significant criticism for stating, “The individuals who linked arms and actively resisted, that in and of itself was violent.”</p><p>In happier Occupy news, a group calling itself <a href=\"http://occupywallst.org/article/occupy-highway-99-march-washington/\">Occupy the Highway</a>, has begun a journey from Wall Street to Washington D.C. taking the message of Occupy Wall Street on the road.</p><p>Finally, the Ukrainian feminist group <a href=\"http://www.businessinsider.com/watch-topless-protest-at-the-vatican-2011-11\">Femen</a> staged a topless demonstration at the Vatican, declaring their rejection of&nbsp; \"Papal patriarchal propaganda manipulated by the medieval idea of a woman\'s social and cultural mission.\"</p><p>From Vermont to the Vatican, that is this week’s Fragments From the Streets. If you have actions you would like us to report, please get in touch with us <a href=\"mailto:kyle@theprecarious.com?subject=Fragments%20From%20the%20Streets\">here</a>. Until then, Happy liberation!</p>','','filtered_html');
