INSERT INTO `field_revision_body` VALUES ('node','article',0,35,38,'und',0,'<p>Roughly 7.9 million homes are in foreclosure across the United States. Though it’s a grim statistic, organizers are using those numbers to their advantage, by recruiting those who have been affected by foreclosure to fight against big banks.</p><p>Recently, The Precarious profiled people who became activists after facing the possibility of losing their homes. &nbsp;</p><p>“You have to get other people involved,” said homeowner Leonard McWilliams. In 2009, protesters helped McWilliams delay foreclosure by making a human chain around his house. In turn, he and his two teenage sons have participated in several actions against banks, including the Mile-High Showdown in Denver last month.</p><p>During the Showdown, members of the<a href=\"http://progressivecoalition.org/\"> Colorado Progressive Coalition</a>&nbsp;protested Wells Fargo’s business practices. Dozens of activists closed a large downtown branch of the bank for part of the afternoon. Cristie Drumm , vice president of communications for Wells Fargo in Colorado, said the bank closed because of safety concerns.</p><p>Massachusetts protesters with<a href=\"http://clvu.org/\"> City Life/Vida Urbana</a>&nbsp;similarly occupied a Wells Fargo in Revere, Mass. on Oct. 28. Some members of that group had been arrested while linking arms outside the headquarters of Bank of America in September.</p><p>Drumm said Wells Fargo understands that many people are frustrated with the weak economy and high foreclosure rates.</p><p>“We’re helping struggling homeowners stay in their homes,” Drumm said. “We’re working hard and we’re committed to doing more.”</p><p>Nationally, The New Bottom Line launched its widely publicized “Move our Money “campaign last week. The goal is to move $1 billion from big banks to credit unions and smaller financial institutions. According to the group, customers have so far moved $50 million from national banks.</p><p>These actions are effective because they grab the attention of mainstream media, said Ben Hanna, organizing director with CPC. Local television, radio and <a href=\"http://www.denverpost.com/breakingnews/ci_19216797\">The Denver Post</a>&nbsp;covered CPC’s week of actions.</p><p>“This is all about visibility,” he said. “We were successful because we were able to communicate to a larger audience.”</p><p>Though some high-profile events have passed, there are ongoing group efforts to stop home foreclosure.</p><p>Sharon McKee credits CPC with helping her save the northeast Denver home she’s lived in for 16 years. She felt like dealing with banks had become a full-time, fruitless job.</p><p>“It becomes your life,” McKee said. Members of the CPC wrote letters to McKee’s bank, demanding a loan modification, which was recently granted. The coalition continues to work on similar efforts with homeowners.</p><p>“Our work hasn’t ended,” Hanna said.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.newbottomline.com/\">The New Bottom Line</a>&nbsp;offers information on getting involved with the fight against home foreclosure nationally.</p>','','filtered_html');
